    <question>
        <prompt>The term "flappers" in the 1920s referred to:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Female factory workers</option>
            <option letter="b">Young women who challenged traditional social norms</option>
            <option letter="c">Progressive Era reformers</option>
            <option letter="d">Conservative religious activists</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Flappers were young women in the 1920s who challenged traditional social and moral conventions. They symbolized the changing role of women in society, characterized by shorter skirts, bobbed hair, jazz music, and more liberal attitudes toward social behavior. Their lifestyle represented the broader cultural changes and generational conflict of the "Roaring Twenties."</explanation>
    </question>
